<sn><md>Some soil enzymes and their roles in the soil

Soil enzymes are biological catalysts that play essential roles in nutrient cycling, organic matter decomposition, and soil fertility. They are produced by soil microorganisms, plant roots, and soil fauna.

Here is a list of important soil enzymes and their functions:

Enzyme	Role in Soil

Urease	Breaks down urea into ammonia and carbon dioxide; aids nitrogen cycle
Dehydrogenase	Indicates overall microbial activity; involved in organic matter oxidation
Phosphatase	Releases inorganic phosphate from organic compounds; supports P cycle
Î²-glucosidase	Breaks down cellulose into glucose; helps in carbon cycling
Arylsulfatase	Releases sulfate from organic matter; involved in sulfur cycle
Amylase	Decomposes starch into sugars; assists in organic matter breakdown
Protease	Breaks down proteins into amino acids; supports nitrogen mineralization
Catalase	Decomposes hydrogen peroxide into water and oxygen; detoxifies soil
Cellulase	Degrades cellulose from plant residues; important in carbon turnover
Lipase	Breaks down lipids into fatty acids and glycerol; aids organic matter decay



